  <!-- ──────────── security & trust ──────────── -->
  <section class="security">
    <div class="container container--wide">
      <header class="sec-head">
        <span class="eyebrow eyebrow--ember">Where keys live</span>
        <h2>Routing happens locally. So do your secrets.</h2>
      </header>

      <ul class="security__list">
        <li>
          <strong>Local-only secrets by default.</strong>
          Provider API keys live in the macOS Keychain with
          <code>kSecAttrAccessibleWhenUnlockedThisDeviceOnly</code>. The Hydrant
          fetches them on-demand for outbound requests; they never reach
          OpenBurnBar's cloud unless you opted into hosted quota refresh.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>BYOK tunnel for Cursor.</strong>
          Cursor's BYOK endpoint speaks to a Cloudflare worker bound to
          <span class="mono">your-handle.openburnbar.dev</span> that forwards
          back into your Mac. Your keys stay on your Mac; the worker is a thin,
          authenticated pipe.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Bound to localhost.</strong>
          The gateway binds <span class="mono">127.0.0.1:8317</span> only. No
          LAN exposure, no public surface, no inbound from outside your Mac.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No plaintext in the relay.</strong>
          When Hermes Remote Relay is enabled, frames are end-to-end encrypted —
          the Cloud Run relay never sees the prompt or the response. The router
          stays on-device.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Every routing decision is logged.</strong>
          The chosen account, the skipped accounts, and the reason for each
          skip (exhausted, rate-limited, model-incompatible) land in a local
          <code>ProviderRoutingDecisionEvent</code> stream you can inspect.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="security__cap mono">
        Source · <code>docs/ROUTED_CLIENT_GATEWAY.md</code> · <code>docs/THREAT_MODEL.md</code> · <code>ProviderRoutingStateBuilder.swift</code>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ──────────── faq lite ──────────── -->
  <section class="qa">
    <div class="container container--wide">
      <header class="sec-head">
        <span class="eyebrow eyebrow--ember">Quick answers</span>
        <h2>The questions we get on every demo.</h2>
      </header>

      <dl class="qa__list">
        <div>
          <dt>What is Provider-Family Failover?</dt>
          <dd>
            The default mode. BurnBar extends your capacity by stretching a
            request across <em>multiple accounts inside the same provider
            family</em>. If your pinned Z.ai key throttles, your MiniMax key
            picks up — both are OpenAI-shape, so the wire format never
            changes. Claude Code requests do the same inside the Anthropic
            family, with your Pro plan as the primary and your Console
            admin key as the runner-up. The mode is honored before ranking
            — failover happens inside the family, never across it.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>What is Intelligent Model Router?</dt>
          <dd>
            The opt-in mode. You tell BurnBar what the task is (or let the
            client surface it) and the router scores every candidate model
            against capability, quota health, cost, latency, context window,
            reliability, and benchmark freshness. The winner serves the
            request; the runner-up is held in reserve. Benchmarks are
            <strong>advisory</strong> — they help break ties and weigh recency,
            but they never override your pin or the live quota state.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Will BurnBar send my Codex task to Claude?</dt>
          <dd>
            Not in failover mode. The router refuses to cross the family
            boundary — your Codex request stays on OpenAI-family accounts,
            even when every one of them is rate-limited (in which case
            you get a structured 503, not a silent rewrite). In intelligent
            mode you can opt into cross-family routing per surface, with the
            client client opting in too. We never silently swap providers
            on a request that asked for a specific one.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Can I still pin a model?</dt>
          <dd>
            Yes — pinning is the strongest signal in both modes. A pinned
            account or pinned model wins as long as it's healthy. In family
            mode the pin is account-level. In intelligent mode you can pin a
            model, a family, or even a specific tier (e.g. "always opus-class
            for the autopilot surface"). The router will still pre-select a
            runner-up so failover is instant if the pin goes unhealthy.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>What benchmark sources does BurnBar use?</dt>
          <dd>
            A curated set of <em>recently refreshed</em>, well-methodologized
            coding benchmarks — currently Aider Leaderboard, LMSys Arena coding
            slice, and SWE-Bench Verified. Each score carries an age and a
            confidence label; older scores are weighted down. The full source
            list ships with each release as a versioned JSON file you can
            audit, and the weighting curve is documented in
            <span class="mono">docs/ROUTER_BENCHMARK_POLICY.md</span>. We do
            not synthesize our own benchmarks — we cite, we don't fabricate.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Are routing logs safe?</dt>
          <dd>
            Yes. The local <span class="mono">ProviderRoutingDecisionEvent</span>
            stream records the chosen account ID, the skipped account IDs, the
            reason each one was skipped, and the final ranking signals — never
            the API key, never the OAuth bearer, never the request body, never
            the response body. Logs stay in the local SQLite store and never
            leave the device unless you explicitly enable an opt-in mirror.
          </dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

